Currently, there is a disconnect between the available options of the JIRA issues macro (see http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/JIRA+Issues+Macro) and the dialog that is presented in the Confluence 4 editor (CTRL+SHIFT+J or the {jira} macro).

Options like the render mode (renderMode) are not supported in the dialog. Via wiki-markup they are and after I enter a {jira} macro successfully via the "add wiki markup" option, it becomes uneditable.

I understand the reasoning behind moving to the new editor, but at least provide support for Atlassian's own macros. I rely heavily on these macros and this prevents me from using 4.0 in production at the moment.

There is a regression in the Blog Posts Macro in Confluence 4.0.  The behavior changed from 3.5.13 and deviates from the functionality previously documented at:
Confluence 3.5: https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CONF35/Blog+Posts+Macro
Confluence 4.0 (as of when this issue was raised): https://confluence.atlassian.com/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=264706932

When using the following markup in 3.5.13 the page would display the full content of 10 blog posts:

{code}
{blog-posts:max=10}
{code}

In Confluence 4.0, the content is displayed as if the "titles" option was selected.  I can't find a way for our users to have their pages render content the same way it did in 3.5.13.

The documentation linked above -is- was clear that the default option *should* be "entire".  _After raising this issue on Sept 21 2011, Atlassian modified the live Confluence 4.0 documentation on October 4 2011 to remove reference to the default "entire" option._

This is a regression and significant for our users, to the point where I and other customers who have commented below may need to revert back to 3.5.13 due to the loss of functionality, so I'm marking it as a -major- critical bug.  This didn't just remove functionality, this removed *DEFAULT* functionality without warning.

