Currently the tab-navigation used for the spaces-list-macro and recently-updated-dashboard-macro reloads the page. This is especially annoying when the macro is located at the bottom of a page, because the reloaded page starts at the top and you need to scroll all the way down to view the results. Please implement a dynamic solution without reloading the page, or at least add some (optional!) anchors to the url and let the reloaded page jump to the results.

h3.Chrome 14 can't displayed attached .swf file on a page

h4.1. Finding
After attaching .swf file to a page. Confluence couldn't show the attached .swf file using _Multimedia_ macro. Instead of displaying, it will be returned as _Missing Plug-In_. It showed as below.
!missing_plugin.png!

h4.2. Cause
The macro generates different mime type when it is displayed as html on Chrome 14. Instead of generated as {{type="application/x-shockwave-flash"}} it was generated as {{type="application/x-shockwave-flash2-preview"}} that cause it couldn't be displayed on Chrome 14.

h4.3. Workaround
*A. Remove the type particular line from _mime.types_ file*
# Stop Confluence
# Navigate to _<confluence_dir>/confluence_WEB-INF/classes_
# Make a backup of _mime.types_ file
# Change the following line
{code}
image/vnd.rn-realflash rf swf
{code}
to this line
{code}
image/vnd.rn-realflash rf 
{code}
# Remove the following line from the _mime.types_
{code}
application/x-shockwave-flash2-preview rf swf
{code}
# Restart Confluence

*B. Embed the file using _html_ macro*
Enable {{{htm}}} macro, and insert macro in a page
{code}
{html}
<embed src="<attachment_path>/swf_file.swf">
</embed>
{html}
{code}

So if in the old setenv.sh we had something like this defined:
{code}
JAVA_OPTS="$JAVA_OPTS -Dhttp.proxyHost=proxy.cas.local -Dhttp.proxyPort=3128 -Dhttp.nonProxyHosts=*.cas.local|192.168.*' -Djavax.net.ssl.trustStore=/opt/atlassian/jssecacerts"
JAVA_OPTS="-Xms256m -Xmx512m -XX:MaxPermSize=256m $JAVA_OPTS -Djava.awt.headless=true "
export JAVA_HOME JAVA_OPTS
{code}

The Auto installer will produce the following setenv.sh:
{code}
JAVA_OPTS="$JAVA_OPTS -Dhttp.proxyHost=proxy.cas.local -Dhttp.proxyPort=3128 -Dhttp.nonProxyHosts=*.cas.local|192.168.*' -Djavax.net.ssl.trustStore=/opt/atlassian/jssecacerts"
export JAVA_OPTS
{code}

The second declaration was ignored. This caused Confluence to run out of memory when upgrading to 4.0

